wcg_strategy: I tried to think of settings, subcultures, and above all else, categories of words, that are completely unrelated to the thing that I'm supposed to not think about.  I first started typing many words, ignoring how the box ignored my single spacebar input to separate the words, so perhaps a character limit on that field could be useful, just in case any future participant makes the same mistake.  I have a friend who practices the art of freestyle rap, and I have spent many hours doing this activity myself, so the "No Food Words" requirement was not new to me.  Thus, it's difficult to say exactly how my background may affect my word choices in this study.
guess_experiment: I don't know exactly what it's trying to measure, but something related to the word associations that people make, or the paths their minds go down when trying to think of random words.
wcg_diff_general: I felt slightly more focused after reading the story.  Because I had just been focusing intensely, it was easier to allow my mind to wander.
wcg_diff_suppress: Most objects that surround me are tangentially related to growing or cooking food, even things like "brick" and "table", so it was hard to suppress thoughts which are "related to food in a secondary or tertiary way".  I found it slightly easier to suppress thoughts related to the story, and I thought that would be more difficult, because I've watched a lot of YouTube content related to murder mysteries and police interrogations.  However, I had to engage my mind to remind myself which things are related to the story, because there are a bunch of unrelated objects that I couldn't use as words, like "rope" and "breakfast".
wcg_strategy_after_fail: I tried to think of categories of things that are specific to a certain task or field or industry that is not related to food.  For the story, I tried to avoid thinking about anything grim, and then I asked myself if the word is somehow related to the story even if it is not related to death.
volition_explanation: It was always unintentional at first, but then, I realized that I need to avoid a list of unrelated words, and this requires me to keep the most important details of the story in mind.
wcg_diff_explanation: I didn't notice any specific changes.  I have played other "timed language puzzle challenge" games in the past and my brain feels similar to how it feels after playing one of those.  Perhaps more energized and focused in the moment, but more tired in terms of how much energy I have until my next break.
open_box: For the first ~minute of the study, I was typing words without hitting enter, and then I erased all of them, and began to type them individually.  I hope this doesn't affect my data too much.

I think it's also trying to measure the type of words that come up into mind when the easiest and freshest thing in mind are both eliminated as options.
wcg_diff_general: Before the story, I had nothing else in my mind, so I was able to focus on items that were around me and listed those as my words. After reading the story, I was thinking about the story most of the time when coming up with words, so I was a little distracted in coming up with words. I kept thinking about words such as murder, death, and blood.
wcg_diff_suppress: When asked about suppressing food-related thoughts, I easily adjusted in eliminating these words in my mind. However, suppressing story-related thoughts was a little bit hard because I kept thinking of scenarios that happened in the story and was trying not to list these words.
wcg_strategy_after_fail: I focused heavily on my surroundings and decided to list these words instead in order to prevent myself from focusing too much on the things that I can't list.
volition_explanation: Glimpses of the story line kept coming back in my mind unintentionally while coming up with words during the game.  I kept thinking about who truly murdered the lady and the situation that Claire was in while being followed. Vivid images and emotions were overtaking my mind while trying to play the word chain game. I was thinking about Stuart taking too much advantage of Claire and not admitting about it.
wcg_diff_explanation: There was a definite emotion change within me after reading the story because the story still lingered in my mind while playing the word chain game. I felt scared but eager to learn more about the story. I wanted to know what was going to happen to Claire until the end. I also felt fatigued after reading the story because I focused heavily to try to remember as much as possible, so my mind was churning too much to come up with words during the word chain game.
open_box: This was an interesting experiment because it's fascinating to find out how the mind can be influenced easily after reading something from somewhere.

wcg_strategy: With regards to word generation, I frequently hopped between different topics. Sometimes, the new word matched the theme of preceding word. But other times, it was a completely random thought.   Before the game started, I primed myself to follow the rules by repeating them in my head multiple times. I also announced it out loud for myself to reinforce it. By doing so, I felt confident in my ability to play the word game according to the rules while also being creative and generative enough.
guess_suppress_1: Avoid thoughts and words about food.
guess_experiment: To see how reading something impacts an individual's chain of thoughts.
wcg_diff_general: It was paradoxical almost. After reading the story, I felt like I could draw upon a wider variety of topics. However, I also felt restricted as any story-related topics were forbidden. Remembering which topics were story-related required much more cognitive effort than blocking out food-related thoughts.
wcg_diff_suppress: I felt that I was more cognizant over food-related thoughts as that was just one category. However, the story-related thoughts covered a variety of topics such as murder, alcohol, technologies, etc. Nonetheless, I FELT confident for both.
wcg_strategy_after_fail: I would say out loud what I was about to type. If I didn't realize it while typing, I certainly would if I verbally announced it. For example, in the first round, I was in the middle of typing "cherry" but upon saying it out loud, I realized it was a food-related thought.
volition_explanation: Details from the story would appear in my head such as the setting. Looking back, I realize that "villa" may have been tangentially related to and influenced by certain elements of the story.
wcg_diff_explanation: At first, I felt like I could draw upon a greater variety of words. I'm not sure about the extent but I definitely felt like I came up with words much more quickly. I also started paying attention to the connotation of words.
